if (!file.exists("met_all.gz")) {
  download.file(
    url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/USCbiostats/data-science-data/master/02_met/met_all.gz",
    destfile = "met_all.gz",
    method   = "libcurl",
    timeout  = 60
  )
}

met <- data.table::fread("met_all.gz")

Step 2

met <- met[temp > -17][elev == 9999.0, elev := NA]
met[, week := week(as.Date(paste(year, month, day, sep = "-")))]
met <- met[week == min(week, na.rm = TRUE)]
met_avg <- met[, .(
  temp = mean(temp, na.rm = TRUE),
  rh = mean(rh, na.rm = TRUE),
  wind.sp = mean(wind.sp, na.rm = TRUE),
  vis.dist = mean(vis.dist, na.rm = TRUE),
  dew.point = mean(dew.point, na.rm = TRUE),
  lat = mean(lat),
  lon = mean(lon),
  elev = mean(elev, na.rm = TRUE)
), by = USAFID] 


met_avg$region <- ifelse(met_avg$lon > -98 & met_avg$lat >39.71, "north east",
                         ifelse(met_avg$lon > -98 & 
                                  met_avg$lat < 39.71, "south east",
                                ifelse(met_avg$lon < -98 & met_avg$lat >39.71, 
                                       "north west", "south west")))

# met <- met[week == min(week, na.rm = TRUE)]
met_avg$elev_cat <- ifelse(met_avg$elev> 252, "high", "low")

The violin plots reveal distinct regional patterns in wind speed distributions. The northeast region shows a distribution highly concentrated at a single value (1.0 m/s), while the northwest region displaysa broader, bimodal distribution with a notable cluster of higher wind speeds. The southeast region exhibits a pattern similar to the northeast, with a sharp peak at 1.0 m/s, and the southwest region demonstrates another bimodal distribution with peaks near 0.5 m/s and 1.0 m/s. Overall, the northwest region appears to have the highest wind speeds, while the northeast region shows the most concentrated distribution around 1.0 m/s.

Step 4

met_avg %>%
filter(!(region %in% NA)) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=dew.point, y=rh, color=region))+ 
  geom_jitter() + 
  stat_smooth(method=lm) 
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The scatter plot demonstrates a positive relationship between dew point and relative humidity across all regions. All regional regression lines show positive slopes, indicating that as dew point increases, relative humidity also tends to increase. The relationship appears strongest in the north east and south east regions, while the north west and south west regions show more scatter in the data. This pattern makes meteorological sense because dew point is a direct measure of the absolute amount of moisture in the air, and as this moisture content rises, the relative humidity will naturally increase, assuming the air temperature does not rise at an even faster rate.

Step 5

met_avg %>%
filter(!(region %in% NA)) %>% 
  ggplot()+
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=elev_cat,fill=region), position = "dodge")+ #Bars by elevation category using position="dodge"
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "PuOr")+ 
  labs(title="Number of weather stations by elevation category and region", 
       x="Elevation Category", y= "Count")+ #Create nice labels on the axes and add a title
  theme_bw()

The bar chart reveals significant differences in weather station distribution across regions and elevation categories. The south east region has the highest number of stations overall, particularly concentrated at low elevations. The north east region shows more stations at high elevations compared to its low-elevation stations , which likely reflects a predominantly mountainous or highland topography. The north west region has the fewest total stations but shows a strong skew, with almost all of its stations located at high elevations. This distribution pattern suggests that the placement of weather stations is not uniform and is likely tied to the distinct geography and topography of each region.

The region with the highest mean dew point (approximately 21 Â°C) is south east, indicating that this region has the most moisture in the air on average. The north west region displays the lowest mean dew point around 12.5 Â°C, suggesting it has the driest air on average. The error bars reveal that the north west and south west regions have the most variable conditions, while the south east region shows the least variability.

Regional differences in wind speed are distinct compared to dew point patterns. The north west and south west regions show higher mean wind speeds around 2.9 - 3.1 m/s with wide confidence intervals, indicating a greater variability in wind conditions. The north east and south east regions display lower mean wind speeds suggesting that they are, on average, calmer.

met_avg2<-met_avg[!is.na(rh)]

top5 <- met_avg2[rank(-rh) <= 10]

rh_pal = colorNumeric(c('blue','purple','red'), domain=met_avg2$rh)#

leaflet(met_avg2) %>% 
  addProviderTiles('OpenStreetMap') %>%
  addCircles(lat=~lat, lng=~lon, color=~rh_pal(rh), 
             label=~paste0(round(rh,2), ' rh'), opacity=1,fillOpacity=1, radius=500) %>%
  addMarkers(lat=~lat, lng=~lon, label=~paste0(round(rh,2), ' rh'), data = top5) %>%
  addLegend('bottomleft',pal=rh_pal, values=met_avg2$rh, 
            title="Relative Humidity", opacity=1)

The relative humidity map reveals a clear east-to-west gradient across the United States. The eastern regions show high relative humidity values (80-90%), represented by pink and red colors. The central regions display transitional humidity levels, while the western regions exhibit low values. The top 10 highest relative humidity locations are predominantly located in coastal regions and near the Great Lakes, which reflects the influence of large bodies of water. This pattern demonstrates how geographic features (like proximity to oceans and mountains) and large-scale meteorological factors affect regional humidity distributions.

The ridgeline plots show clear temperature differences by region and elevation. At high elevations, the north east region has the coolest temperatures around 18Â°C, while the south west region shows the warmest and most variable distribution. At low elevations, all regions are warmer than their high-elevation counterparts, with the north east and south east regions reaching 25â26Â°C. The south west region maintains the most consistent temperatures across both elevation categories, while the north west region shows dramatically different patterns between high and low elevations. This demonstrates that both region and elevation are critical drivers of temperature, and that these two factors can interact to create unique local climate patterns.
